english:
  title: A Record of the Illuminated Moon
  author: Jung Yio
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Venerable One is a station beyond my knowing. Eochon, Gong Baekgong, sent me a letter requesting: "The monk Hae Ching once studied under Muhak, and Muhak wrote the two characters 'Illuminated Moon' and gave them to Hae Ching as his dharma name. Many years have passed now, and no one has yet expounded their meaning. Thus I come to you seeking this record, and you must not refuse me."

    I have heard it said that in the lands of the Western Regions, those who shave their heads and don robes of faded hue are called bhikshus—mendicant monks. They beg from the buddhas above for dharma to nourish their wisdom-nature, and beg from donors below for rice to sustain their bodies. As the faculties of each are keen or dull, delusion and awakening differ. Thus one must seek out an elder master of great attainment to receive their awakening words.

    When Muhak called upon this name "Venerable One," he meant that all beings possess a nature of void brilliance and true awakening. When the spirit is purified, the mind stilled, conceptual knowing dissolved, and the bonds of fabrication cut, then one's luminous awareness expands to encompass heaven and earth, to contain all ten thousand things, transcending the boundaries of ancient and modern times alike.

    Consider how the bright moon hangs in clear sky: its reflection enters water and becomes rivers and streams, valleys and marshes, lakes and gorges. Though the vessels differ in form, the reflected light remains unchanged. The moon itself remains as it was. Yet the moon possesses no light of its own—it receives the sun's radiance. As distance from the sun varies, the light received waxes and wanes. Only when directly opposite does the light become full. Thus from the new moon to the full, the distance increases, and the light gradually grows until it reaches its zenith. From full moon to dark, the distance decreases, and the light gradually diminishes until nothing remains. This is the principle of heaven and earth's swelling and emptying, giving and receiving.

    As for that which I have received from heaven: this luminous void is what is called the luminous virtue. When it expands and shines forth, there is nothing it does not illuminate. There is no waning or waxing, no beginning or end. It fills the ten directions completely, pure and all-pervading. How could it yield to the moon? Rivers and streams, valleys and marshes, lakes and gorges—all exist within the space of my heart as the complete and wondrous functioning of mind itself. This is the moon at the moment of fullness. Let the Venerable One ponder this well.
  footnotes:
    - Muhak (無學) was a renowned Korean Buddhist master of the Goryeo period, known for his Zen teaching.
    - The term 'Illuminated Moon' (照月) draws on Buddhist metaphors where the moon represents Buddha-nature and illumination represents awakening.
    - The philosophical framework here blends Buddhist concepts of emptiness and luminous awareness with Neo-Confucian ideas of the 'luminous virtue' (明德), reflecting Korean intellectual synthesis of these traditions.
    - The contrast between the moon's apparent waxing and waning versus its unchanging nature represents the relationship between phenomenal appearances and the unchanging nature of consciousness in Buddhist philosophy.
